oc:kn_2df3864f a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When timing referral prompts" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Ask for referrals at high-intent moments: right after the first 'aha' moment, after achieving a milestone, after exceptional support, or after renewing/upgrading." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Customers are most likely to refer when they've just experienced value, making these the optimal trigger moments." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_308bc0b4 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing the referral user experience" ;
    oc:directiveContent "The referral loop must be frictionless: Trigger Moment → Share Action → Convert Referred → Reward → Loop. Each step should require minimal effort. One-click sharing outperforms multi-step flows." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Every additional step in the sharing process causes drop-off. The best programs (Dropbox, Uber) made sharing nearly effortless." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_75eeb42c a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:SuccessIndicator ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When measuring referral program health" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Referred customers typically show 16-25% higher LTV and 18-37% lower churn compared to organically acquired customers. A healthy program sees 10-25% of customers referring. K-factor > 1 indicates viral growth." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These benchmarks help calibrate expectations and identify whether a program is underperforming or excelling." ;
    oc:severityLevel "LOW" .

oc:kn_8cad4053 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Prerequisite ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before starting any referral program task" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Check for .agents/product-marketing-context.md (or .claude/product-marketing-context.md in older setups) before asking the user questions. Use existing context and only ask for information not already covered." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Avoids asking redundant questions and ensures recommendations are grounded in the product's actual positioning and market context." .

oc:kn_b8a48394 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When diagnosing underperforming referral programs" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Low referral participation is usually caused by one of five problems: low awareness of the program, complex sharing process, weak or single-sided incentives, poor timing of the ask, or inadequate placement in the product." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Most referral program failures trace back to these five root causes rather than product-market fit issues." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_d69307b6 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When choosing incentive structure" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Double-sided incentives (both referrer and referred benefit) convert better than single-sided rewards. Use single-sided only for high-value products where the referrer reward alone is compelling." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Double-sided incentives create a win-win framing that makes sharing feel generous rather than self-serving, increasing both share rate and conversion rate." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_e2bb61c8 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When sizing referral incentives" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Max Referral Reward = (Customer LTV × Gross Margin) - Target CAC. Never exceed this ceiling or the referral channel becomes unprofitable." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The reward must leave room for gross profit after acquisition cost. Exceeding this math turns the program into a loss leader." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_efc14e2d a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building any referral or affiliate program" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Do not launch a referral program without fraud prevention measures: email verification, device fingerprinting, delayed reward payout, minimum activity thresholds, and clear terms of service." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Without fraud controls, self-referrals, referral rings, and coupon site abuse can drain program budget and corrupt attribution data." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

